                <h5>Two Ways of Creating Lab-Grown Diamonds</h5>
                <p>As the name quite literally suggests, lab-grown diamonds are grown in laboratories. A diamond that is created in a laboratory could also be known as lab-made, man-made, engineered or cultured. Diamonds can be grown in laboratories in one of two ways. Firstly, they can be created by mimicking the earth’s natural high pressure and temperature environment. If this is the case, these diamonds will be called high-pressure, high-temperature or HPHT diamonds and they will be manufactured in a large mechanical press. The other process is known as chemical vapour deposition (CVD). CVD diamonds are created by using a seed of a diamond and then growing it layer by layer in a chamber known as a plasma reactor. These laboratory creations are formed in just a few weeks and look exactly like natural diamonds, with the same chemical composition as them.</p>
                    <h5>Formation of Natural Diamonds</h5>
                    <p>Natural diamonds, on the other hand, are formed roughly 200 kilometres below the earth’s surface. Diamonds form naturally when pure carbon undergoes incredibly high pressure and temperature conditions within the earth’s mantle for several years. These diamonds take a few hundred years to be formed and require extensive mining to be uncovered and used commercially.
